Hi, my name is
Andrew Ba Tran, and I'm

2
00:00:07,910 --> 00:00:09,618
a data reporter for
the Washington Post's

3
00:00:09,618 --> 00:00:10,640
investigative team.

4
00:00:10,640 --> 00:00:13,670
And I'm here to talk
about the opioid files

5
00:00:13,670 --> 00:00:16,219
and how we investigated
pharmaceutical companies,

6
00:00:16,219 --> 00:00:19,340
and the government, and
made data accessible to all.

7
00:00:19,340 --> 00:00:23,350
This is a two-week-year-old boy
in an isolation ward in West

8
00:00:23,350 --> 00:00:25,500
Virginia.

9
00:00:25,500 --> 00:00:30,120
Any sound seriously disturbs
him and he won't stop crying,

10
00:00:30,120 --> 00:00:33,330
and that's because he was
born addicted to opioids.

11
00:00:33,330 --> 00:00:36,000
And he is one among
thousands of children

12
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:38,040
separated from the
parents and families

13
00:00:38,040 --> 00:00:41,370
and forced into state care
by an opioid epidemic that

14
00:00:41,370 --> 00:00:44,850
has fractured families in
every corner of the country.

15
00:00:44,850 --> 00:00:48,690
In West Virginia alone,
more than 5,200 lives

16
00:00:48,690 --> 00:00:52,500
over the past three
decades have been lost.

17
00:00:52,500 --> 00:00:54,960
And we've seen the
effects of this.

18
00:00:54,960 --> 00:00:57,250
We know that the
number of children

19
00:00:57,250 --> 00:00:59,250
in foster care in West
Virginia has doubled ever

20
00:00:59,250 --> 00:01:02,440
since the epidemic started.

21
00:01:02,440 --> 00:01:05,209
And other effects that
we've been able to see

22
00:01:05,209 --> 00:01:08,660
are the death rates in
communities across the country.

23
00:01:08,660 --> 00:01:13,580
In West Virginia, we can see
the effects of the opioid death

24
00:01:13,580 --> 00:01:17,120
rates and we can also
see that there were also

25
00:01:17,120 --> 00:01:19,610
higher rates of child
abuse and neglect claims

26
00:01:19,610 --> 00:01:22,067
in those same areas.

27
00:01:22,067 --> 00:01:23,650
State officials say
that more than 80%

28
00:01:23,650 --> 00:01:25,750
of children in
foster care have been

29
00:01:25,750 --> 00:01:28,950
affected by the drug epidemic.

30
00:01:28,950 --> 00:01:31,290
So we've seen the effects.

31
00:01:31,290 --> 00:01:34,470
We've never really been able
to see the causes before,

32
00:01:34,470 --> 00:01:37,750
not with a lot of specificity.

33
00:01:37,750 --> 00:01:41,730
The thing is, pharmaceutical
companies and the Drug

34
00:01:41,730 --> 00:01:43,230
Enforcement
Administration have been

35
00:01:43,230 --> 00:01:45,970
able to see this
for the longest time

36
00:01:45,970 --> 00:01:49,720
because every single pill a
manufacturer, the distributor,

37
00:01:49,720 --> 00:01:54,020
the pharmacy is
tracked in the dataset

38
00:01:54,020 --> 00:02:00,090
and it's called the automated
reports and consolidated order

39
00:02:00,090 --> 00:02:00,590
system.

40
00:02:03,740 --> 00:02:05,510
And the Drug Enforcement
Administration

41
00:02:05,510 --> 00:02:08,130
is also under the
Department of Justice.

42
00:02:08,130 --> 00:02:12,060
And in fact, because
prescription pain pills are

43
00:02:12,060 --> 00:02:17,490
scheduled-2 drug which means it
has a high potential for abuse,

44
00:02:17,490 --> 00:02:20,190
with use potentially leading
to severe psychological and

45
00:02:20,190 --> 00:02:22,760
physical dependence.

46
00:02:22,760 --> 00:02:25,070
And we call it ARCOS for short.

47
00:02:28,180 --> 00:02:31,290
And so pharmaceutical
companies and the government

48
00:02:31,290 --> 00:02:32,940
have known the
scope of this data

49
00:02:32,940 --> 00:02:37,700
for the longest time, the reach
of the spread of these pills.

50
00:02:37,700 --> 00:02:39,200
And journalists and
researchers have

51
00:02:39,200 --> 00:02:42,500
tried to get this dataset
for the longest time as well.

52
00:02:42,500 --> 00:02:45,250
But we've only been able to
get it at the aggregate level,

53
00:02:45,250 --> 00:02:49,170
maybe by state, maybe by
county, maybe by zip code,

54
00:02:49,170 --> 00:02:51,665
maybe by overall
drug, but we've never

55
00:02:51,665 --> 00:02:53,540
been able to get it at
the raw data set level

56
00:02:53,540 --> 00:02:57,080
where we could really dig
into the nuances of the data.

57
00:02:57,080 --> 00:03:02,280
Every time we've made a request
for it, it's been denied.

58
00:03:02,280 --> 00:03:04,830
That is until recently.

59
00:03:08,650 --> 00:03:10,360
So for context, the
most powerful people

60
00:03:10,360 --> 00:03:13,198
in the pharmaceutical America
didn't want it released.

61
00:03:13,198 --> 00:03:14,740
And a lot of the
most powerful people

62
00:03:14,740 --> 00:03:17,560
